Now, what are non-convergent sequences?
The spec claims the fixed point is unique non-zero. But what about sequences where amplitude goes to 0? If amplitude becomes 0, then further interference yields 0. So 0 is a sink.
What about entropy? For self-interference, en → clamp(en - 256) (approximately). Since clamp at -32768, eventually any finite sequence of self-interferences will hit -32768 and stay there if amplitude remains non-zero. But if amplitude becomes 0, entropy no longer matters? The spec doesn't define 0-amplitude wave vectors as special, but interfere(0, anything) might produce certain results.
